that began in Germany and continued in exile. Connecting movements, forms, and themes such as Dada, multi-perspectivity, and the urban experience with the theory and practice of psychoanalysis, she illuminates themes distinctive to the Berlin psychoanalytic context such as war trauma, masculinity and femininity, race and anti-Semitism, and the cultural avant-garde. In particular, she explores the lives and works of Alfred Döblin, Max Eitingon, Georg Groddeck, Karen Horney, Richard Huelsenbeck, Count Hermann von Keyserling, Ernst Simmel, and Arnold Zweig.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aArtistsxBiographyxGermanyxBerlin. 0aArtistszGermanyzBerlinvBiography. 0aAuthors, GermanxBiographyxGermanyxBerlin. 0aAuthors, GermanzGermanyzBerlinvBiography. 0aModernism (Aesthetics)xHistoryx20th centuryxGermanyxBerlin. 0aModernism (Aesthetics)zGermanyzBerlinxHistoryy20th century. 0aPsychoanalysis and culturexHistoryx20th centuryxGermany. 0aPsychoanalysis and culturexHistoryx20th centuryxNew York (State)xNew York. 0aPsychoanalysis and culturexHistoryx20th centuryxPalestine. 0aPsychoanalysis and culturezGermanyxHistoryy20th century. 0aPsychoanalysis and culturezNew York (State)zNew YorkxHistoryy20th century. 0aPsychoanalysis and culturezPalestinexHistoryy20th century. 0aPsychoanalystsxBiographyxGermanyxBerlin. 0aPsychoanalystszGermanyzBerlinvBiography. 7aHISTORY / Europe / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook Package 2000-2015z978311066334108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311069042240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520950382423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780520950382.jpg  a978-3-11-066334-1  UC Press eBook Package 2000-2015c2000d